    <item>
      <title>Github Pages, Hugo and Cloudflare</title>
      <link>https://blog.pakithecat.eu/posts/2025/githubpages-cloudflare/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 03 Jul 2025 12:18:07 +0300</pubDate>
      <guid>https://blog.pakithecat.eu/posts/2025/githubpages-cloudflare/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h3 id=&#34;how-to-route-your-github-pages-site-through-cloudflare-on-a-subdomain&#34;&gt;How to route your GitHub Pages site through Cloudflare on a Subdomain&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Do you have a site hosted on &lt;strong&gt;GitHub Pages&lt;/strong&gt;, like &lt;code&gt;https://usergithub.github.io/my-blog/&lt;/code&gt;, and want to access it via a &lt;strong&gt;custom subdomain&lt;/strong&gt; (e.g., &lt;code&gt;blog.yourdomain.com&lt;/code&gt;) using &lt;strong&gt;Cloudflare&lt;/strong&gt;? It&amp;rsquo;s a great way to improve your performance, security, and have a cleaner URL. Here&amp;rsquo;s how you can do it, step-by-step!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;step-1-prepare-your-domain-in-cloudflare&#34;&gt;Step 1: Prepare Your Domain in Cloudflare&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you haven&amp;rsquo;t done this essential step already, you&amp;rsquo;ll need to &lt;strong&gt;add your main domain&lt;/strong&gt; (such as &lt;code&gt;yourdomain.com&lt;/code&gt;) to Cloudflare. This process involves changing your domain&amp;rsquo;s nameservers to those provided by Cloudflare &lt;a href=&#34;https://developers.cloudflare.com/dns/zone-setups/full-setup/setup/&#34;&gt;(see docs)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>OCI - Attach and mount a block volume</title>
      <link>https://blog.pakithecat.eu/posts/2025/oci-mount-block-volume/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 16 Feb 2025 16:27:00 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://blog.pakithecat.eu/posts/2025/oci-mount-block-volume/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Follow the Oracle &lt;a href=&#34;https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Block/Tasks/connectingtoavolume_topic-Connecting_to_iSCSIAttached_Volumes.htm&#34;&gt;guide&lt;/a&gt; to attach the newly created volume and these steps:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&#34;identify-the-new-drive-eg-devsdb&#34;&gt;Identify the New Drive (e.g., &lt;code&gt;/dev/sdb&lt;/code&gt;)&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo fdisk -l
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h4 id=&#34;create-a-partition-if-needed&#34;&gt;Create a Partition (If Needed)&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo fdisk /dev/sdb
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Press &lt;code&gt;n&lt;/code&gt; to create a new partition.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Choose partition type (&lt;code&gt;p&lt;/code&gt; for primary)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Select the default values or specify size.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Press &lt;code&gt;w&lt;/code&gt; to write changes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&#34;format-the-partition&#34;&gt;Format the Partition&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h4 id=&#34;create-a-mount-point&#34;&gt;Create a Mount Point&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo mkdir -p /mnt/mydrive
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h4 id=&#34;mount-the-drive&#34;&gt;Mount the Drive&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/mydrive
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h4 id=&#34;auto-mount-on-boot&#34;&gt;Auto-Mount on Boot&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get the UUID of the partition&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo blkid /dev/sdb1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Edit the &lt;code&gt;/etc/fstab&lt;/code&gt; file&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo nano /etc/fstab
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Add this line at the end&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nv&#34;&gt;UUID&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;o&#34;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&amp;lt;your-uuid&amp;gt;  /mnt/mydrive  ext4  defaults,noatime,_netdev  &lt;span class=&#34;m&#34;&gt;0&lt;/span&gt;  &lt;span class=&#34;m&#34;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Save and exit&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to use GPG to encrypt/decrypt files</title>
      <link>https://blog.pakithecat.eu/posts/2025/gpg/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 03 Jan 2025 15:24:43 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://blog.pakithecat.eu/posts/2025/gpg/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;GnuPG uses public-key cryptography so that users may communicate securely. In a public-key system, each user has a pair of keys consisting of a private key and a public key. A user&amp;rsquo;s private key is kept secret; it need never be revealed. The public key may be given to anyone with whom the user wants to communicate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;installation-and-key-pair-generation&#34;&gt;Installation and key pair generation&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;install GnuPG on Debian / Ubuntu&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo apt-get install gnupg
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;generate a new GPG key pair&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;let&amp;rsquo;s use as an example the email address &lt;code&gt;johndoe@example.com&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;gpg --full-generate-key
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;exchanging-keys&#34;&gt;Exchanging keys&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;exporting a public key in a binary format&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;gpg --output johndoe.gpg --export johndoe@example.com
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;or ASCII&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;gpg --armor --output johndoe.gpg.pub --export johndoe@example.com
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;importing a public key&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;gpg --import janedoe.gpg
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;gpg --list-keys
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;validate the imported key (manual, if needed)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;gpg --edit-key blake@cyb.org
#display the fingerprint
fpr 
#sign the key 
sign
#check the key
check
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;encrypting-and-decrypting-documents&#34;&gt;Encrypting and decrypting documents&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;encrypting&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;gpg --output doc.gpg --encrypt --recipient janedoe@example.com doc.txt
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;decrypting&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;gpg --output doc-dec.txt --decrypt doc.gpg
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>WinSCP - sudo after login</title>
      <link>https://blog.pakithecat.eu/posts/2025/first/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 03 Jan 2025 10:55:00 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://blog.pakithecat.eu/posts/2025/first/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Recently, I had to upload some folders to a Linux server (Oracle Cloud), but the user permissions I had did not allow me to create the necessary folders. While searching for a solution, I came across this possibility.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In some cases (with Unix/Linux server) you may be able to use &lt;code&gt;sudo&lt;/code&gt; command straight after login to change a user, before file transfer session starts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;em&gt;SFTP&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;SCP&lt;/em&gt; protocols allow for this, but the actual method is platform dependent.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
